JupyterHub Deployment on GCP (Using Podman & Podman Compose)

1. Create a VM on Google Cloud Platform (GCP)
 . Use Ubuntu as the base image.
 . Allow HTTP and HTTPS traffic.
 . Create a firewall rule to allow inbound traffic on port 8000 (JupyterHub will run on this port).

2. SSH into the VM and Install Dependencies

 . sudo apt update
 . sudo apt install git -y
 . sudo apt install podman -y
 . sudo apt install podman-compose -y

3. Clone the Project Repository
 
 . git clone https://github.com/Gourav-saini1/Jupyter-project.git
 . cd Jupyter-project/jupyter-hub/


4. Start JupyterHub with Podman Compose

 . podman-compose up -d
 . podman ps   "this will show you up container"

Then open your browser and go to:
http://<SERVER_EXTERNAL_IP>:8000

Note: At this stage, the application will load but you may encounter a 500 Internal Server Error when starting the Jupyter server.


5. Fixing the 500 Internal Server Error

 . export DOCKER_SOCK=/run/user/1001/podman/podman.sock
 . export DOCKER_SOCK_GID=$(stat -c '%g' "$DOCKER_SOCK")
 . systemctl --user enable --now podman.socket
 . systemctl --user start --now podman.socket

6. Restart JupyterHub

 . podman-compose down
 . podman-compose up -d

7. Access the Application

http://<SERVER_EXTERNAL_IP>:8000
Now JupyterHub and the Jupyter server should work without issues.









